[3] Mozambique
Date: Fri, 16 Apr 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200404160650.html>

Cholera Claims More Lives And Spreads Further
--------------------------------------------------
The current Mozambican cholera epidemic has claimed 3 more lives in Maputo
and Sofala provinces this week, and has spread to the district of Mocuba,
in Zambezia province, although no death from the disease has been notified
here, reports the Fri, 16 Apr 2004 issue of the Maputo daily "Noticias".
2 of the deaths occurred in Sofala, and the other was reported in Maputo.
In Mocuba, 14 cases of cholera have been diagnosed in the past week.
Also in Zambezia, on Thu, 15 Apr 2004, 7 patients were hospitalized with
cholera in the district of Namacurra, 6 in the provincial capital,
Quelimane, and one in Nicoadala. This brings to 1016 the total number of
cases in Zambezia since late Jan 2004, when the 1st case was diagnosed.
However, only 10 of these patients have died.
With the latest fatality in Maputo, the death toll in the Mozambican
capital has now reached 38 since the outbreak began in Dec 2004. The death
toll in Sofala now stands at 27.
Maputo is by far the worst-hit part of the country -- but the epidemic is
clearly waning, since there are now only between 50 and 70 new cases a day
being reported, compared with about 350 patients a day at the peak of the
epidemic, in Jan 2004.
There were 119 hospitalized patients at the Cholera Treatment Center (CTC)
at Maputo's Mavalane General Hospital on Thu 15 Apr 2004, including the 63
admitted that day.
Maputo city Health director Olivia Ferreira told reporters that, though
this may be described as an improvement, the health authorities are
insisting on maintaining preventive measures, and are still on full alert.
"We are recording a certain drop in terms of cholera in Maputo city, but we
also record some increases on rainy days, particularly in the suburbs with
the worst sanitation conditions. We must note, however, that both new
admissions and the number of hospitalized patients has been dropping", she
said.
In Sofala, the chief doctor for the province, Flavio Wate, said that the
situation is gradually coming under control, and the number of new cases is
dropping by the day.
Sofala had 70 hospitalized cholera patients on Thu 15 Apr 2004, of whom the
great majority (51) were in the provincial capital, Beira.
******
[4] Mozambique
Date: Mon, 12 Apr 2004 21:54:16 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@ntlworld.com>, Dr Rana Jawad Asghar
<jawad@alumni.washington.edu>
Source: News24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/Africa/News/0,,2-11-1447_1511297,00.html>

Health authorities in Vilankulo district in southern Mozambique said on
Mon, 12 Apr 2004 that they have confirmed at least 22 cholera cases in the
past week.
It is the first time the outbreak that began in Dec 2003 has been detected
in Vilankulo, 400 km northeast of Maputo, the capital. In the rest of the
country, more than 100 people have died and thousands have been sickened by
the outbreak.
A report on state radio said laboratory analysis by the Inhambane
provincial hospital confirmed the cases in Vilankulo after complaints
emerged in recent days of cholera symptoms such as diarrhea and vomiting.
The World Health Organisation, the Mozambican health ministry and others
have vaccinated thousands of people since the outbreak began. 2 doses of
the oral vaccine, given in successive weeks, protect patients for at least
a year.
New cases continue to be reported in Maputo, and other areas, though the
numbers are smaller than in previous months during the height of the outbreak.
In Maputo, health authorities say about 70 more people a day are seeking
help, down from a height of 350 new patients daily.
"We have been recording relatively small numbers of patients at the wards,
and that puts us more at ease, although it also means that more work should
be done to bring these figures even lower," said Olivia Ferreira, the
Maputo city health director.
