[ 7] India (Dysentery)
Date: Wed 14 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Kerala.com [edited]
<http://www.asean-disease-surveillance.net/ASNNews_Detail.asp?ID=1328>

Dysentery Claims 5 Lives in Gorakhpur, India
-------------------------------------------------
At least 5 children have died in the last 2 days in Gorakhpur, India, as
hospitals reported an alarming rise in dysentery cases. Dozens more are
seriously ill and hospitals are overflowing with more and more children
being brought in everyday.
A common ailment, the disease has taken on serious proportions as a severe
heat wave has led to water shortage, forcing villagers to draw water from
untreated sources like rivulets. Worried parents have traveled hundreds of
kilometers to Gorakhpur to get their children treated.
"The epidemic started 3-4 days back and we expect more patients. If primary
aid is given to them then they can be saved. 5 children have expired. Daily
10-15 children are being admitted in the OPD (Out Patients Department),"
R.K Gupta, junior doctor at the city's main medical college, said. State
authorities say all efforts are being taken to prevent the epidemic from
spreading.
*****
[8] Bangladesh (Diarrhea)
Date: Wed, 14 Apr 2004
From: ProMEDmail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Star, Bangladesh [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/2004/04/14/d40414070257.htm>

Diarrhea in 34 Sailkupa Villages, Bangladesh
---------------------------------------------
2 persons died of diarrhea in Sailkupa upazila in Jhenidah district in the
last 2 days. At least 5000 people have been affected by the disease, Civil
Surgeon Dr Nazrul Islam told newsmen after a visit to the affected areas.
The dead were aged 4 and 85 years. Both died on Mon, 12 Apr 2004.
The disease has spread to 34 villages in 5 Unions in the upazila, district
health officials said. The civil surgeon said the situation is under
control now after 9 medical teams started working in the area. 3 camps have
been opened.
About 100 patients have been admitted to upazila health complexes at
Sailkupa and Sripur (Magura). The disease spread quickly as those attacked
remained at home instead of going to hospitals for treatment, the civil
surgeon said.
But Abdul Bari, chairman of Dhalaharchandra Union Parishad in the affected
area (when contacted over the phone) said the disease is spreading and more
people are being attacked.
He said besides medicine, food should be supplied in the area as relief, as
many people are starving because their bread-earning male members have been
disabled by the disease.
During a visit to Sailkupa health complex yesterday, some patients told
this correspondent that they were not getting adequate medicine. "A doctor
gave me a slip to bring medicine from outside, but pharmacists told me this
medicine is available only at government hospitals", an affected patient said.
